g.title: Folded Corner.69
g.desc: Façade pattern compliments SRP on the subsystem level, becaus...

g.text: Façade pattern compliments SRP on the subsystem level, because it decouples details from the client, by restricting them to a limited interface. Firstly, it provides more control over the execution flow of the software. More control will results in less unforeseen scenario’s, resulting in fewer bugs and thus stability. Secondly, because the responsibility of the façade is shifted from the client to a dictated class we produce enhanced readability on client side. Thirdly, reusability of execution sequences across the code-base.

g.title: Folded Corner.97
g.desc: The Façade pattern facilitates layering between subsystems. E...

g.text: The Façade pattern facilitates layering between subsystems. Each subsystem communicates to a single, limited interface of the other subsystem. This makes change and re-use easier. We can ‘swap’ subsystems with less impact, because there is low coupling.

g.title: Folded Corner.138
g.desc: A well designed software sub-system will have multiple classe...

g.text: A well designed software sub-system will have multiple classes all serving a single responsibility. This results in multiple interfaces all around the subsystem. This can be ‘overwhelming’ and complex (e.g. order dependent object use) for certain clients that only use combinations of specific operations of that subsystem. The Façade pattern can help with unifying objects within a subsystem as a goal to provide a simplified interface. I.e.: Façade facilitates an abstraction, by grouping objects of a subsystem, to provide a simplified interface to the client.

g.title: Folded Corner.189
g.desc: Restriction is a result of simplification. The Façade pattern...

g.text: Restriction is a result of simplification. The Façade pattern provides a limited, simplified interface to the client. Restriction prevents clients from interacting with the system in a ‘unforeseen’ way that might result in failure or damage to a system. The larger the interface of a system the harder it will become for us as software engineers to oversee all possible error scenario’s. Restriction gives us more control over execution.

g.title: Folded Corner.196
g.desc: The façade unifies subsystem classes. This unification can be...

g.text: The façade unifies subsystem classes. This unification can be identified as a ‘god’ like object. However, in the non-strict sense the Façade has one responsibility, namely to cluster and delegate object calls to simplify interfacing to a subsystem. However, we have to carefully monitor if the façade will not become the place to make quick and easy fixes by adding responsibilities there, because it is after all an unified ‘place’ where a lot of objects come together. A ‘God’ object is the inverse of SRP. It will be hard to introduce new changes, bring it under test and analyze problems.

g.title: Folded Corner.202
g.desc: Façade pattern compliments OCP, because of decoupling clients...

g.text: Façade pattern compliments OCP, because of decoupling clients from low level details of a sub system. Decoupling simplifies change in the lower level details of the subsystem, without affecting clients. This has positive effect on production and test code stability. Less recompilation and modification in existing code will be required.
